<F P=101> PHILIPPINES </F>
<H3> <TI>   AFP Chief Claims Narcom Personnel Involved in Drug 
Trafficking </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0701132194 Quezon City GMA-7 Radio-Television Arts Network 
in Tagalog 0930 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0701132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City GMA-7 Radio-Television Arts Network 
in Tagalog 0930 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Tagalog </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Philippine National Police Narcotics Command 
[Narcom] leads the list of government personnel implicated in 
drug trafficking. This was revealed in a letter to Defense 
Secretary Renato De Villa by General Lisandro Abadia, chief of 
staff of the Armed Forces of the Philippines [AFP]. 
  According to Abadia, some officials and personnel of Narcom 
are able to sell illegal drugs that have been confiscated. 
Narcom operatives are allegedly giving protection to drug 
pushers in exchange for big pay-offs or bribes. 
  In light of this, Abadia has proposed a system to safeguard 
confiscated drugs and to reveal law enforcers involved in drug 
pushing. 
  Meanwhile, Abadia's accusations were immediately denied by 
Narcom Chief Ramsey Ocampo. Ocampo admitted that some Narcom 
personnel may be involved in drug pushing, but, it does not mean 
that the whole command is involved in drug trafficking. 
  [Begin Ocampo recording in progress] ...unscrupulous 
activities of some of our personnel. The complexities mentioned 
by Gen. Abadia are based on previous perceptions. [sentence as 
heard] As a matter of fact, their claims of service from the 
admissions of small-time drug pushers that were arrested before, 
well, it is normal that the arrested drug pushers will accuse 
Narcom operatives of involvement in irregularities. So far, we 
have not handled a case where there has been no counter-charge 
against us. 

</TEXT>

