<F P=101> PAKISTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Program Launched To Curb Drug Menace in Tribal Areas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0101150094 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 1 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0101150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A four-phased program is being launched to locate 
and destroy heroin laboratories and punish those behind this 
nefarious trade in the tribal areas. The Frontier Corps and 
Antinarcotics Task Force will work jointly to implement the 
program. A high-level meeting in Islamabad today reviewed 
various aspects of the prevailing narcotics problem in the 
country. Federal minister for interior and narcotics control, 
Major General, retired, Nasirullah Khan Babar, presided over the 
meeting which was also attended by governor of NWFP [North-West 
Frontier Province], Major General, retired, Khurshid Ali Khan, 
and other senior officials. The meeting considered mechanics to 
eliminate the cultivation of poppy and cannabis and decided to 
involve tribal elders in this process. Stress was laid on 
adoption of strict measures to eradicate drug abuse and 
interdiction of illicit narco-trafficking. It was decided that 
a comprehensive legislation should be enacted to effectively 
deal with all aspects of the drug menace before its extension to 
FATA [Federally Administered Tribal Areas]. 

</TEXT>

