<F P=101> FINLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Exceptionally Large' Drug Ring Uncovered </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20205A Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 24 Nov 93 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20205A </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Finnish News Service Report: "Large Narcotics Gang </F>
Uncovered"] 
  [Text] The Narcotics Violations Office of the Helsinki 
Police is in the midst of investigating a narcotics ring that is 
exceptionally large for Finland. Over the course of the 
investigation, the police have held 85 persons for questioning 
and charged 20 with smuggling and distributing narcotics. 
  On Tuesday [23 November], the case came up for trial in 
Helsinki Municipal Court, where the prosecutor read an 
indictment for aggravated narcotics violations against a 
25-year-old man from Kervo. Further indictments are expected 
against the other members of the gang. 
  The gang has been operating in the Helsinki region, the 
Turku 
area, and [other places] on the west coast. It is suspected of 
having distributed and sold tens of kilograms of hashish, much 
heroin and amphetamines, as well as the drugs LSD and ecstasy, 
both of which have rarely been found in Finland. 
  The police seized a little over 1 kg of hashish and around 
100 kg of amphetamines, as well as small amounts of other drugs. 
  Gang members are between age 17 and 35 and most have never 
had prior involvement with the police. The suspected gang leader 
worked full time on narcotics trafficking. 
  The gang has been operating for approximately one year, and 
has constantly grown by recruiting new members. The police 
believe the organization has spun off a number of smaller 
subgroups, which remained loosely tied to each other. 
  The police got on the gang's trail last spring. The full 
extent of the case is still not known. The police will still not 
say from where the drug ring originated. 
  This drug ring is not the same one confirmed a short time 
ago 
of distributing "superheroin." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

