<F P=101> FINLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian-Born Israeli Citizen, Others Sentenced for 
Distributing Hashish </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20208A Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT in Finnish 12 Dec 93 p 
B 4 </F>

<F P=103> 94P20208A </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Four Imprisoned in Vantaa 11-Kg </F>
Hashish Case"] 
  [Text] Four men were sentenced to prison in Vantaa 
Municipal Court for distributing some 11 kg of hashish. The 
hashish, which was brought in from Russia, was sold in nearby 
Helsinki. About 1.5 kg were seized in the arrest. The main 
figure in the hashish ring is thought to be Keijo Changklung 
(formerly Saira), who was sentenced to a prison term of 32 
months for selling 7.5 kg. He will have no chance of early 
parole. Petri Niemela received a sentence of 26 months for 
having purchased 3.2 kg of the substance from Changklung, and 
another 2.7 kg directly from Russia. 
  Previously sentenced in the case was Kari-Pekka Diomin, who 
bought 2.5 kg of hashish from Changklung. Diomin was sentenced 
to a year in prison, with no possibility of parole. 
  The Russian-born Israeli citizen Gay Dagan received a 
one-year prison term, with possibility of parole, for having 
distributed a shipment of drugs received from a Russian citizen. 
  The East Uusimaa Area Investigation Unit, which is 
headquartered in Vantaa, handled the case, since it was the 
first to learn of the drug selling activity. The drugs were sold 
in nearby areas of Helsinki, i.e., in the Martina Restaurant on 
Hameetie and in the Cafe Miina in Hakaniemi. 
  Those convicted were also ordered to pay damages to the 
state 
amounting to a total of 70,000 markkas. 

</TEXT>

