<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wasmosy Proposes Creating Southern Cone `Association' To 
Combat Drug Trade, Money Laundering </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1401192294 Asuncion ULTIMA HORA in Spanish 14 Jan 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> PY1401192294 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion ULTIMA HORA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Paraguayan] President Juan Carlos Wasmosy arrived 
in Buenos Aires this morning. He will probably propose an 
association of Southern Cone governments, in what could be 
called the resurgence of the "Condor Operation," to fight 
eventual subversive outbursts similar to that provoked by the 
Zapatista movement in Chiapas, Mexico. 
  Argentine media sources commented on a meeting between 
[Argentine President] Carlos Menem, [Uruguayan President] Luis 
Alberto Lacalle, and Wasmosy in Punta del Este last weekend, 
during which the presidents reportedly expressed concern for the 
possible entry, through the Bolivian and Paraguayan borders, of 
alleged guerrillas who would attempt to destabilize local 
governments. 
  Asked about the subject shortly before leaving for Buenos 
Aires, Wasmosy denied that the issue had been discussed during 
the Punta del Este meeting. He said, however, that the matter 
could possibly be raised this time around, adding that if this 
were the case he would propose the association of the three 
countries' armies and intelligence services. Asked about his 
government's proposal if the issue of guerrilla activities were 
discussed at the mini-summit, Wasmosy said: "An association. 
Let us hope all countries will join efforts--armies as well--to 
fight drug trafficking, money laundering, and crime in general. 
That is the objective. We had a meeting of general staff 
chiefs to discuss the matter recently. I think we have made 
progress." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-60124 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptdd003__l94005" </HT>


