<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Airport Supervisor Claims U.S. Aircraft `Never Answered Our 
Calls' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1701032294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1800 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1701032294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nelly Gomez in Barranquilla; from the "NTC News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] The U.S. airplanes that overflew Barranquilla 
yesterday are participating in narcotics operations with the 
national government's authorization. What is unclear is why 
they flew so close to the ground when their route was authorized 
by the Colombian Air Force at 22,000 feet. 
  The two U.S. military airplanes overflew Barranquilla for 
eight hours and endangered air navigation in Colombia, according 
to Henry Jimenez, supervisor of the Ernesto Cortizos Airport 
control tower. The pilots never reported their position or 
altitude; all they did was identify themselves with the names of 
Cajun 680 Alpha and Cajun 57 Alpha. 
  [Begin Jimenez recording] They never answered our calls. 
That is why they might have caused a collision with controlled 
civilian aircraft. No one could tell what were the aircraft's 
positions or altitude at a given moment. [end recording] 
  According to the official, the U.S. aircraft were in a 
critical airspace coordinate, meaning a route designated for 
civilian aircraft on the Barranquilla-Santa Fe de Bogota-New 
York route, crossing through Curazao and vice versa. 
  The military aircraft left for Howard Air Force Base, 
Panama, 
at 1900. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

