<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alleged Drug Traffickers' Properties in Tamaulipas Seized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WB0017B Mexico City EXCELSIOR STATES SECTION in Spanish 15 
Dec 93 pp 1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> 94WB0017B </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR STATES SECTION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Enrique Pedroza Flores] </F>
  [Text] Ciudad Victoria, Tamaulipas, 14 December--Since last 
February the Office of the Attorney General of the Republic 
[PGR] and district judges seized approximately 80 farms and 55 
residences from presumed drug traffickers in Tamaulipas. This 
announcement was made today by the director of the state's 
Public Property Register, Francisco Gerardo Campos Martinez. 
  Although not citing statistics, he claimed that the number 
of 
confiscations far exceeds those made of landed properties last 
year. 
  This increase is a result of the intensified action on the 
part of the Office of the Attorney General of the Republic to 
combat the drug traffic since Carpizo McGregor became head of 
that department. 
  He stressed: "What has occurred is just a reflection of a 
more persistent battle against the drug trade by the PGR." 
  As for the confiscations, Campos Martinez claimed that most 
of the real estate and rural properties involved are located in 
the municipalities of Matamoros, Reynosa, Nuevo Laredo, and 
Miguel Aleman. 
  It should be noted that the judges and the PGR will maintain 
the impoundments until a determination is made of whether or not 
the owners are guilty of the illicit acts charged. 
  Finally, the official revealed that, in some instances, as 
many as two farms and several residences have been seized from a 
single presumed drug trafficker. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

