in Nicaragua </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2201000294 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 20 Jan 
94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PA2201000294 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, Government Minister Arnoldo Oriz Moscoso 
said he plans to counter drug trafficking in Central America in 
1994 by reinforcing international agreements. 
  He gave the information outside the National Palace after 
being asked what he knew about the arrest of Guatemalan citizen 
Velmar Espina Novo, who was involved in a cocaine shipment in 
Nicaragua. Ortiz said: "For the time being we have no official 
information only that a person was arrested. We will therefore 
solicit information on the alleged Guatemalan drug trafficker 
and the alleged member of the military, Byron Robeto Morales." 
  He said there are signed agreements on antidrug trafficking, 
which will be put into effect with the United States, Colombia, 
Mexico, and the remaining isthmian countries. Ortiz admitted 
Guatemala is becoming more and more a bridge for drugs and a 
storage center as well. 
  Regarding the death of inmates in penitentiaries, he said 
each case is being investigated, although most deaths seem to be 
prompted by fights or personal vengeance. 

