<H3> <TI>   Authorities Downplay DEA Role in Popoyo Beach Operation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2001030594 Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0100 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2001030594 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0100 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Excerpts] Deputy Government Minister Frank Cesar said the 
drug operation in Popoyo Beach, Rivas was staged by Nicaraguan 
authorities. The DEA only supplied information as part of a 
cooperation protocol signed with Nicaragua. 
  Nicaragua maintains a constant battle against drug 
trafficking. The last operation that took place in Rivas, where 
275 kg of cocaine were seized, is a demonstration of this 
effort. Since 1991, Nicaragua maintains relations and exchanges 
information with the DEA. Information exchanges are also 
maintained with narcotic information centers in Mexico, 
Colombia, and Costa Rica. The Popoyo Beach operation was 
basically carried out by Nicaraguan authorities. Here is what 
Deputy Government Minister Frank Cesar said: 
  [Begin Cesar recording] We spoke with the DEA information 
center about the Popoyo operation because it had information on 
aircraft overflights too. The information they gave us 
contributed to the success of this operation. Nevertheless, I 
want to point out the operation was carried out exclusively by 
Nicaraguans. More than 50 National Police agents were involved, 
although a couple of DEA agents, who we had given prior approval 
to, did participate. They have some technical facilities that 
allow operations such as these to be a success. [end recording] 
  In another turn of events, Cesar said the airplane that made 
an emergency landing at Puerto Cabezas was because it ran out of 
fuel. Two Peruvians were traveling in this aircraft. The police 
searched the aircraft but no drugs were found. 
  [Begin Cesar recording] It is a matter of concern when an 
airplane runs out of fuel and makes an emergency landing. We 
have photocopies of their passports and the names of the people 
who were aboard the aircraft. We have all the necessary 
information; however, nothing was found. [end recording] 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

