<F P=101> SOUTH KOREA </F>
<H3> <TI>   20 Kg of Cocaine Discovered on Ship Docked at Ulsan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P30021 Seoul TONG-A ILBO in Korean 25 Dec 93 p 29 </F>
<F P=103> 94P30021 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul TONG-A ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Summary] On 24 December the ROK National Maritime Police 
seized 20 kg of cocaine, worth an estimated $50 million, off a 
freighter undergoing periodic repairs at the Hyundai Mipo 
Dockyard in Ulsan. Police began searching the 
Panamanian-registered Sunny Ocean on 22 December after receiving 
a tipoff. Two days later they found 20 kg of cocaine stored in 
two plastic containers hidden in a seawater intake port. Police 
are investigating 13 Korean crew members, including the ship's 
captain, Kim Chun-ung. Authorities think that the crew was 
asked by a foreign drug-smuggling organization to transport 
South American cocaine, and that they intended to deliver it to 
a drug-trafficking group in the South Korea-Japan region. 
Police commented that the cocaine was more likely intended for 
a third country, because the amount of cocaine involved is 
enormous when compared to the size of the ROK cocaine market. 
The freighter is owned by the Kitaura-kai [transliterated] 
Ocean Shipping Company of Japan, and travels mainly between 
Japan, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Singapore, Argentina, Uruguay, and 
Brazil. It was returning to Japan after visiting Brazil, 
Argentina, and Hong Kong when it docked at Ulsan on 21 December 
to undergo periodic repairs. 

</TEXT>

