<F P=100> NEAR EAST &amp; SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> PAKISTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Editorial Calls for `Serious' Antinarcotics Efforts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WD0135D Lahore NAWA-I-WAQT in Urdu 2 Dec 93 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0135D </F>
<F P=104>  Lahore NAWA-I-WAQT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Urdu </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Anti-Narcotics Operation"] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto has approved plans to 
launch a major government operation against cultivation and 
smuggling of narcotics in the nation. She said in the high-level 
meeting of the Anti-Narcotics Task Force at her house that the 
major drug smugglers will be arrested at any cost and political 
pressure of any kind will not be accepted. As for cultivating, 
use, and smuggling of narcotics in our country, it is still on 
the rise. The situation is so serious that this trade is 
regularly protected by some circles in our country. Some members 
of the law enforcement agencies are also allegedly involved in 
it. Now they discuss political patronage for this trade openly. 
The U.S. government went as far as to say that some persons in 
the legislature are also involved in this trade. The drug trade, 
in addition to increasing the number of drug abusers, has also 
given the United States and Western nations an opportunity to 
denounce Pakistan. Our economic aid was also stopped because of 
this. There is no doubt that the "drug Mafia" in Pakistan has 
become very powerful during the last few years, and it has the 
blessings of the administration, law enforcement agencies, and 
politicians. The drug trade within the country is carried out 
under the supervision of this Mafia. Despite the efforts of 
government law enforcement agencies, heroin factories in tribal 
areas still have not been destroyed. The drugs smuggled from 
Afghanistan are available in addition to it. Although the Saudi 
government has sentenced some Pakistanis to death recently and 
also has given Pakistan a list of smugglers, the big fish of the 
Mafia has not been apprehended. The efforts to control this 
Mafia started during General Ziaul Haq's time, however, only 
minor dealers were arrested. This determination was announced by 
the governments that followed Zia, however, the drug Mafia was 
never really affected. During the caretaker government, names of 
some of the big fish were published, and a series of raids were 
started. Some of them were arrested, however, those who control 
this trade, and whom the Pakistani agencies know well, were not 
arrested. It is clear from the record that the efforts to catch 
the big fish or the drug lords have been nothing more than 
slogans. Now Madam Bhutto's government has made this 
announcement all over again. We expect that some serious work 
will be done and the proposed operation is not just paperwork. 

</TEXT>

