<F P=100> NEAR EAST &amp; SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> SAUDI ARABIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saudi-French Antinarcotics Symposium Held in Riyadh </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2301212094 Riyadh SPA in English 1908 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2301212094 </F>
<F P=104>  Riyadh SPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riyadh, Jan 23, SPA -- The Director of Public 
Security General Ahmad Bin Mohammad Bilal [spelling as received] 
opened the first Saudi-French anti-narcotics symposium here on 
Sunday. 
  Delivering the inaugural address General Bilal said the 
symposium is the outcome of positive cooperation between 
anti-narcotics authorities in the kingdom and France. 
  He praised the efforts exerted by the Saudi Government to 
provide security and stability for both citizens and residents. 
  He reviewed agreements signed by the kingdom in the field of 
combating narcotics and stressed that Saudi Arabia has enacted 
several extremely deterrent regulations to curb drug smuggling 
or trafficking. 
  He said the kingdom has also gone a long way in 
international 
and regional cooperation to combat narcotics. 
  The acting director of the anti-narcotics department and 
supervisor of the symposium Brigadier General Darwish Bin 
Ibrahim Faqiha [spelling as received] said the symposium was 
held in line with the directives of Interior Minister Prince 
Nayif Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz who is extremely keen on fighting 
narcotics in the Arab world in general and the kingdom in 
particular. 
  He said the kingdom exerts intensive efforts to combat 
narcotics on the basis of a number of concepts foremost among 
which is the commitment to Islam and original Arab traditions. 
  He said the kingdom is among the least affected countries by 
the narcotics problem because of the Saudi Government's keeness 
on the security and safety of the citizens and the homeland. 
  He stressed that the kingdom has never had one incident of 
growing, producing or making illegal drugs of any kind and that 
the death penalty has been applied to deter drug traffickers, 
smugglers and carriers. 
  He added that out of his conviction that drug addicts are 
sick persons who need medical and psychological treatment, 
Prince Nayif has ordered that addicts be treated as such and 
three specialized hospitals have been established for this 
purpose in Riyadh, Jeddah and Dammam. 
  He said the anti-narcotics department, in collaboration with 
the national anti-narcotics committee chaired by the President 
of Youth Welfare Prince Faysal Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz, implements a 
comprehensive strategy on preventive awareness against illegal 
drug abuse. 
  The head of the French central anti-narcotics bureau 
delivered a speech in which he pointed to the importance of 
Saudi-French anti-narcotics cooperation and expressed hope that 
this cooperation would continue. 
  Saudi and French officials and experts are participating in 
the four-day symposium. 
  The inaugural session was attended by the French ambassador 
to the kingdom and several Saudi officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

